Inferring demography using an end-to-end deep learning approach, using dnadna¶

We are given a dataset of simulations of bacteria with variable population size. Bacteria have (for most of them) a single and circular chromosome. They are haploid.

In some of the simulations, there is a mutation that provides a selective advantage to the individual, meaning that this bacteria will have on average more offsprings per generation. If the size of the population is constant, the frequency of this mutation will increase, and may reach fixation (present in 100% of the population) or not. This mutation was added in the middle of the simulated chromosome. In reality, there is no middle since the chromosome is circular.

The goal of this session is to build a neural network that is able to infer the size of the population through time. This is a regression task.

We can infer either the time and strength of the change in population size, or infer the size at different time steps.

Parameters used for the simulations¶

Simulations were performed using SLiM, a forward in time simulator. Populations go through a bottleneck or an immediate expansion whose timing and amplitude are drawn randomly. In some of the simulations, there is a SNP under selection, where again, the time of apparition and the strength of selection are randomly drawn. At the end of the simulation, 600 individuals (or haplotypes) are drawn.

Genome are 2 Mb long, mutation rate and recombination rate are also dranw randomly.

Inferrence using dnadna¶

dnadna is a software whose aim is to help researcher develop and reuse deep learning methods for population genetics inferences.

It implements the four main steps to facilitate the development of this type methods.

  • simulation
  • preprocessing
  • training
  • prediction

We will use all of the steps except the simulation one, which is time-consuming, and not the core of dnadna since people usually have their simulations.

dnadna init : setting up input data¶

In this case, we already have our simulation done. They are located under the DATAPATH variable we defined earlier.

We need to tell dnadna where is the data, and how they are formatted, if they are already simulated.

We create a dataset_config file to tell dnadna where is our data, and how it look likes.

  • data_root is where the root directory of the dataset is
  • dataset_name is the name of the directory of the dataset

Basically, your dataset will be structured like this:

data_root 
     \__ scenario_001
         \__ replicate_1.npz
         ...
     \__ scenario_002
     ...
  • scenario_params_path: The path to the table we saw above. It has to contain a column scenario_idx, a column n_replicates and as many columns as there are parameters to learn. There can be additional columns.
  • data_source: Describes how the data is organized. The format dnadna assumes that each SNP matrix and associated positions array are stored together in a single NPZ file, either compressed or uncompressed, under the 'SNP' and 'POS' keys respectively.

dnadna preprocess : preprocess input data¶

Sometimes we have constrains imposed by the network, and to prevent the training precedure from crashing, we discard some of the simulations because they have too little SNP or individuals.

During this step, we will also:

  • split the dataset in training, validation and test (optional) sets
  • tell dnadna which parameters we want to regress on. dnadna will then normalize the data (if we do a regression), so all predicted data are of the same order of magnitude and have a similar weight when computing the loss.
  • Other transformations on these parameters can be applied, such as log-transformation if needed.

We edit the file created at the previous step (DLModel/DLModel_preprocessing_config.yml) to set how we want the preprocessing to occur.

Below is a snippet that will generate the section learned_params for the preprocessing config file. To run it, change the cell to code by typping y in control mode (other jupyter mode is edition, when you write within the cell).

Copy and paste the output in the corresponding section of the preprocessing config file. You can switch this cell back to 'raw' to remove the long output by typping r, or hide the cell by clicking on the vertical blue (or orange) bar.

Another section of the preprocessing, is to chose the proportion of your dataset that is going to be used for training, validation and test sets.

To have not too long training time, we recommand chosing:

dataset_splits:
    # portion of the dataset to use for training
    training: 0.1

    # portion of the dataset to use for validation
    validation: 0.01

    test: 0.01
What are the different uses of these 3 sets ?

Finally, we want to remove scenarios which have too few SNP (< 400). This is a constrain of some of the network we will use. We also want to keep simulations with at least 50 sampled individuals.

In the preprocessing config file, we thus have :

preprocessing:
    # minimum number of SNPs each sample should have
    min_snp: 400

    # minimum number of individuals in each sample
    min_indiv: 50
If there are many cpus on your machine, you can use them for speeding up pre-processing. With e.g. n_worker: 4
Jupyter-lab tip: You can right-click on a cell and "Enable scrolling for Outputs", so very long output won't take all the space Additionnaly, you can (left) click on the the vertical blue bar on the left of each cell to hide it.

Once the configuration file for preprocessing is filled and saved, we can start the preprocessing:

The configuration file for the next step is written in DLModel/DLModel_training_config.yml

dnadna train : Train your network !¶

Chose your hyperparemeters (in the config file), your architecture (pick a net among those available, or create your own as a plugin, and go ! And try again !

Available hyperparameters :

  • The network itself : has the biggest influence.

    • You can start by using the CustomCNN and then the SPIDNA implemented in dnadna. Later we will see how to create your own network
    • n_snp and n_indiv are parameters that can be specified in the training config file under network->params. If not specified they are inferred automatically from a data sample.

  • The optimizer : Adam is considered one of the best, but feel free to pick the one you want among those available here.

    • parameters of the optimizer :
      • learning rate : represents somehow the speed at which the network learns. It can have important impact.
      • other parameters that depends on the optimizer you choose.
  • Batch size: How many samples are fed to the network at once between optimization steps. Very large batches tend to overgeneralize (and may not fit onto GPU's memory)
  • n_epoch: Number of time the entire dataset is fed to the network for training
  • dataset transformations: you can decide to add some constrain or augmentation on your data.
    • crop: you can decide to crop your matrices up to a given number of snp or individual (haplotypes). If you don't crop, matrices have different size, which may not work given the network you chose. If matrices have different sizes, for computational reasons, they need to be padded with -1 to have them with the same dimensions.
    • subsample: you can decide to subsample randomly your matrice.
    • keep_polymorphic_sites: tells whether you want to remove sites that are not snp anymore, because you removed all the individuals with the derived allel by subsampling or cropping.
    • your own transformation as a plugin, as shown later.

The evaluation interval (in number of batches), tells when the validation should occur. Having too many evaluation steps increase the time of training, so it's better to have about 3 evaluations per epoch for this tutorial. In one epoch, there is $\frac{size\_training\_set}{batch\_size}$ steps. So dividing this by 3 gives you the interval to have 3 evaluations step per epoch.

In [41]:
# Compute evaluation interval variable

# This value can be changed to what you wrote in your config file
batch_size = 8 # number of SNP matrices processed simultaneously

n_train = df_pre_param.splits.value_counts()["training"]
steps = 3 # number of evaluation you want to perform per epoch
print("Number of training step per epoch:", int(np.ceil( n_train*n_rep / batch_size)))
print("In your config file, set evaluation_interval to:", int( n_train*n_rep / batch_size / steps))

Number of training step per epoch: 52
In your config file, set evaluation_interval to: 17
Try to answer the following questions; - Which network design make sense ? - When running on enough data: does one has better performance (what expremiment(s) would be required to reply to this?) - Do you observe any impact if you modify hyperparameters ? Which ones ? Does it improve the performance or not ?
Note about how to run various experiments. The DLModel/DLModel_training config.yml is a pivot configuration file and can be overwritten each time you run an experiment. In this file, there is run_name_format: run_{run_id} which is going to be the name of the folder created each time we launch dnadna train. This folder contains everything needed to reproduce a given run. run_id will be a number, increasing with runs. To help you keep track of your different experiment, you can modify it with something like: e.g run_name_format: run_MLP_lr0.001_bs256_{run_id}, if you train with a MLP, a learning rate of 0.001 and a batch size of 256.
Every cell that starts by ! something are actually shell command, and can be executed in a terminal, that you can open within jupyter lab the + button in the upper left. Doing so will allow you to execute other thing in the terminal while the network is training
Before executing the next command line, here are tricks to make the training faster and less computationnally heavy when you do not have access to a GPU cluster. For the sake of the tutorial you will edit the training config file: - Do NOT use all SNPs set crop param to max_snp: 400 - Do NOT use all individuals set crop param to max_indiv: 50 (you'll see another transform that you could use) - use GPUs whenever possible (not today) - increase batch_size as much as possible (i.e. so that it will still fit in the available memory), e.g. to 16, 32, 64 .. - decrease n_epochs , e.g. to 1 - reduce the number of evaluation steps (=validation steps) by increasing evaluation_interval see the cell for computing this number, a few step above

dnadna predict : Use an optimized network for prediction on a dataset¶

Prediction is done via a simple forward pass of the data through the fixed network (i.e. the weights are fixed and correspond to weights optimizing the performance during training)

Remark : If one wants to perform prediction on a dataset that did not go through preprocessing, and if the network or training had constrains on the minimum number of SNPs or individuals (such min_snp: 400) , using the option --preprocess will make sure that the same preprocessing is applied to the new simulations/datasets.

Performing predictions with our trained network¶

We just trained a few networks. We will assess performance of the best network on a test set. Since we ask to create a test set during preprocessing, we can get the corresponding file names first and we give this file name to the predict sub-command.

The following cell get the filenames of the test set.

Beware of the path !

Below is a temporary fix required before using dnadna predict.

This will not be required in dnadna new version.

We apply manually the transformations necessary before prediction as they are not applied automatically for now. In particular respecting the input dimension is important, unless you trained a network that is invariant to input dimensions (both number of individuals and snps) and was exposed to various sizes while training (so that it would be robust to new dimensions never seen before)

In [293]:
# Temporary fix, waiting for dnadna new version 
# This will apply the mandatory transforms 

def predict_after_transf(path_to_net, path_to_test_list, crop, colnames=df_param.columns[:-1]):

    p = pred.Predictor.from_net_file(path_to_net)

    test_predict=dict()
    with open(path_to_test_list) as files:
        for test_file in files.readlines():
            test_file = test_file.rstrip('\n')
            snp_sample = SNPSample.from_file(test_file)
            #print(test_file)
            x, _, _ = crop((snp_sample, None, None))
            if x.n_snp < crop.max_snp:
                print(f'skipping prediction for {test_file} (not enough snps after cropping individuals and keeping polymorphism sites only)')
                continue
            try:
                test_predict[test_file] = p.predict(x.tensor.type(torch.float)).to_scalars()
            except:
                print(f'Warning: skipping prediction for {test_file} of size:')
                print(snp_sample.n_snp, crop.max_snp)
                print(snp_sample.n_snp< crop.max_snp)
                print(x.shape)

    df = pd.DataFrame(test_predict).T
    if not colnames is None:
        df.columns = colnames
    df['path'] = df.index
    df["scenario_idx"] = df.path.str.split("/").apply(lambda x: int(x[-2].split("_")[1]))
    df.set_index("scenario_idx", inplace=True)
    return df

Analysing the predictions¶

Here you can analyse the prediction in regard of the data you have. Maybe you can try to propose new training strategy.

In [260]:
def RMSE(df):
    """
    With respect to df_param, compute the Root Mean Square Error per senario line.
    There can be many scenario lines
    """
    try:
        df = df.drop(["path"], axis=1)
    except KeyError:
        pass
    diff = (df - df_param.drop(["n_replicates"], axis=1)).dropna()
    mse = diff ** 2
    return np.sqrt(mse)

In [338]:
def plot_scenario(scn, df, ax=None, c="k"):
    """
    plot all replicates (if present) of the prediction for a given scenario
    """
    if ax is None:
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(8, 5))
    df = df.loc[scn]
    if isinstance(df, pd.Series):
        ax.plot(df, c, lw=1)
    else:
        for r in df.loc[scn].iterrows():
            ax.plot(r[1].drop("path"), c, lw=0.5, alpha=0.4)
    ax.plot(df_param.loc[scn].filter(regex="T\w{2}"), "k", lw=1)

Create you own network with plugins¶

Network plugin¶

We've used an architecture that already exist, but you can create your own network in pytorch. The only difference compared to strictly pytorch network, is that your network object does not inherit from torch.nn.Module but from dnadna.nets.Network. This is a base class used to let dnadna knows that a this network exists.

In [150]:
%%writefile mynet.py

import torch
import torch.nn.functional as F
from torch.nn.functional import relu
from torch import nn
from dnadna.nets import Network

class MyCNN(Network):
    def __init__(self, n_features, n_outputs):
        super().__init__()
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(1, n_features, kernel_size=3, stride=2, bias=False)
        self.bn1 = nn.BatchNorm2d(n_features)
        self.pool = nn.MaxPool2d(2, 2)

        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(n_features, 20, kernel_size=3, stride=2, bias=False)
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(480, 5)  # constraint for 400 snp and 50 indiv.
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(5, n_outputs)

    def forward(self, x):
        batch_size = x.size(0)
        x = x.unsqueeze(1)
        x = self.pool(relu(self.conv1(x)))
        x = self.bn1(x)
        x = self.pool(relu(self.conv2(x)))
        x = x.view(batch_size, -1)  # flatten the tensor for each batch element
        x = relu(self.fc1(x))
        x = self.fc2(x)
        return x

Writing mynet.py
Ask yourself what are conv layers, fc layers, relu and pooling operations? There is a BUG, ON PURPOSE, in this code, you will get an error when running !dnadna train ... in the next section ("dnadna train with plugins") It seems that the dimensions are not correct (ie there's a discordance between the output of a layer and the required output of the next. You can use !dnadna train ... --debug to get more information and try to debug by updating the my_net file

Transformation plugin¶

We can also create transformation plugins if you want to apply a particular transformation.

Below you can write your own, or try to write a transformation that randomize the individuals.

In [ ]:
%%writefile mytransform.py

from dnadna.transforms import Transform

class MyTransform(Transform):
    def __call__(self, data):
        sample, lp, scen = data
        snp, pos = sample.snp, sample.pos
        
        <Create you own transformation here>
        
        sample = sample.copy_with(snp=snp, pos=pos)
        return (sample, lp, scen)
Help if you do not know where to start: You can see an example in mytransform_exampleA.py Which can be added to the training config file within the dataset_transforms section dataset_transforms: - crop: max_snp: 400 max_indiv: 50 keep_polymorphic_only: true - mytransfom_exampleA - snp_format: concat - validate_snp: uniform_shape: false And then applied during training thanks to the plugin mode: !dnadna train DLModel/DLModel_training_config.yml --plugin mytransform_exampleA.py
What is mytransform_exampleA doing? Is it useful for CustomCNN training? And for an exchangeable network like SPIDNA?

dnadna train with plugins¶

Don't forget to change the name of the network and parameters (n_features: 5) in the training config file ! Same for your transformation

e.g in the training config file:

# name and parameters of the neural net model to train
network:
    name: MyCNN

    # net parameters for CNN
    params:
        n_features: 5
